Skyrim GM Guide
This guide provides the tools and advice you need to run adventures in the world of Skyrim using this system. Your role is to be the storyteller, the referee, and the world itself. Your goal is to create a fun, fast-paced, and memorable experience for your players.
1. The GM's Mindset: The Spirit of the Game
This system is built for heroic, narrative-driven action, not for gritty, granular simulation. Keep these principles in mind:
Keep the Pace High: This is designed for one-shots. Don't get bogged down in minutiae. If a rule is slowing things down, make a ruling and move on. The goal is to get from the tavern to the dungeon boss and the reward in a single session.
Say "Yes, but..." or "Yes, and...": When a player wants to do something creative, try to enable it. Instead of a flat "no," introduce a complication or an interesting consequence. This is the core of the "Success with a Complication" rule.
Fail Forward: A failed roll shouldn't stop the story cold. Instead of "you fail to pick the lock," make it "you fail to pick the lock silently, and you hear the Draugr on the other side stir." Failure should introduce new challenges, not end the adventure.
Be a Fan of the Characters: You are not playing against the players. Your job is to present exciting challenges that allow their characters to be awesome. Celebrate their victories and make their struggles feel meaningful.

2. Setting Difficulties: When a Stat Isn't Enough
Sometimes, a player's action isn't against a passive object; it's against a difficult circumstance. For these situations, you can apply a bonus or penalty to the player's Target Number for that specific roll.
Very Easy: +4 to TN. (Success is highly likely).
Easy: +2 to TN. (The task is routine or simple).
Standard: +0 to TN. (The default difficulty for most adventuring tasks).
Hard: -4 to TN. (The task requires training, specialized tools, or is performed under duress).
Very Hard: -6 to TN. (The task is improbable for the average person).
Nearly Impossible: -8 to TN. (The task requires luck or mastery).
Impossible: -14 to TN. (The task is not possible for an average person to even attempt.)
Mythic: -20 to TN. (The absolute ceiling of task difficulty. Reserved for feats of legend; success requires extraordinary stats, stacked advantages, or a critical. -20 is a "find a way," never a "no.")
THIS IS THE ONE TRUE DIFFICULTY LADDER. It is identical everywhere it appears (Reference tables, players guide, Called Shots). -20 is the hard ceiling for ordinary task difficulty; only the Contest Level-Gap Penalty below may exceed it, because it measures power gap between beings, not task difficulty.
Opposed Checks: When a player's action is directly opposed by an NPC (like arm-wrestling or sneaking past a guard), both roll against their relevant stats. If the player succeeds their roll AND the NPC fails theirs, the player succeeds. If both succeed, the one who rolled lower (further from their target number) wins.
Contest Level-Gap Penalty: This applies specifically to WILL-VS-WILL contests — resisting compulsion/domination, contested intimidation, or any check where you are directly resisting another being's attempt to override your action or intent. It does NOT apply to opposed physical/skill checks like arm-wrestling or stealth (use Opposed Checks above for those), and it does not apply to environmental, task-based, or lore rolls (set those difficulties by feel, as normal).
When the opposing being's AP Tier exceeds yours, apply a penalty to your Target Number based on the gap in AP:
Gap of 1-4 AP: No penalty.
Gap of 5-9 AP: -5 to TN.
Gap of 10-14 AP: -10 to TN.
Gap of 15-19 AP: -15 to TN.
Gap of 20-24 AP: -20 to TN.
Gap of 25+ AP: -25 to TN.
This penalty REPLACES the standard difficulty modifier for that roll — it does not stack with Hard/Very Hard/etc. Always use whichever penalty is larger (more severe).
Why this exists: a towering gap in power should feel survivable-on-a-miracle, not impossible. A -20 or -25 penalty is not a "no" — it is a "you need a critical success, a stat far above the norm, or an outside advantage to even have a chance," which sets the precedent that the players can close the gap through play (buffs, allies, leverage) rather than simply being told they cannot act. When a Master-tier antagonist (like a AP 30-35 apex threat) is not directly resisted, the GM may simply narrate their action succeeding without a roll — the penalty above only governs the case where a player character chooses to contest it.
Managing the Enchanter: The Mathematics of Magic
When a player commissions a magic item using the rules in the Items list, your role is to sanity-check their request against the power of the soul they provide. You say "Yes" to the concept, then check the Soul Gem to determine the numbers.
Your Role: Say "Yes" to the concept, then check the Soul Gem to determine the numbers.
The Golden Rule: Use the Spell List to determine damage. If they want a "Ring of Fireballs," it does the damage of the Fireball spell. The Soul Gem determines if the item is powerful enough to hold that spell.
1. Binding Spells (Damage & Effect)
When a player binds a spell to an item (either to Cast it or Strike with it), the Soul Gem limits the Tier of the spell they can use.
Petty Soul: Supports Novice spell effects (e.g., Flames - 3 Damage).
Grand Soul (White): Supports Apprentice & Adept spell effects (e.g., Fireball - 9 Damage).
Black Soul: Supports Expert spell effects (e.g., Incinerate - 12 Damage). Note: Using an item bound with a Black Soul triggers a catastrophe check on a Nat 20 failure.
(These example damages come straight from the Spell List, which is always the authority for spell numbers.)
2. Stat Bonuses (Target Numbers)
Petty Soul: +1 to Stat Score.
Grand Soul (White): +2 to Stat Score.
Black Soul: +3 to Stat Score.
(Reminder: The absolute hard cap for any Stat Score is 22. No combination of items can push a player beyond this).
3. Pools (HP/FP)
Petty Soul: +2 Max.
Grand Soul (White): +4 Max.
Black Soul: +6 Max.
4. Regeneration (The Hard Caps)
Regeneration breaks the economy of the game. It is restricted to high-level souls.
Health Regen (HP)
Petty: Impossible.
Grand (White/Black): +1 HP at the start of the turn.
Hard Cap: A player can never regen more than 2 HP per turn total, even if they wear multiple items.
Focus Regen (FP)
Petty: Impossible.
Grand (White): +1 FP at the start of the turn.
Black Soul: +2 FP at the start of the turn.
Hard Cap: A player can never regen more than 5 FP per turn total.

