3. Building and Running Combat Encounters
Combat should be fast, evocative, and easy to manage. This framework allows you to create challenging encounters that scale as your players grow from competent heroes into mythic legends. The core principle is that enemies are built just like characters: they have Might, Agility, Magic, and Guile scores, which they use to perform all their actions.
A. The Tiered Threat System
Every creature has a Threat Level (TL) from 1 (Minion) to 3 (Boss). Its power scales based on the party's current Tier of play. The creation process is now unified into a single, powerful table.
Step 1: Determine the Party's Tier
First, determine the party's Tier based on their average Advancement Points (AP). These bands are THE canonical tier definitions, used identically by every table in every document.
Novice Tier (0-3 AP): Competent local heroes.
Apprentice Tier (3-6 AP): Regional up-and-comers.
Adept Tier (6-9 AP): Well-known hold champions.
Expert Tier (9-15 AP): Legendary heroes of Skyrim.
Master Tier (15-25 AP): World-saving legends.
Mythic Tier (25+ AP): Beings of living myth. This tier has no upper bound — the system's AP tree fully buys out around 181 AP (every skill Mastered, every stat at its cap), a soft ceiling no realistic campaign reaches. Mythic-tier enemies are built from FLOORS, not tables: the rules state minimums and trust the GM to scale upward to the party (see the Scaled Monster table in Reference tables).
Step 2: Generate the Enemy's Complete Stats
Cross-reference the enemy's Threat Level (TL) with the Party's Tier in the SCALED MONSTER STATISTICS table in GM Guide/Reference tables. That table is the SINGLE authoritative source for enemy stat arrays, HP, Damage, and DR at every tier (Novice through Mythic), with Legendary-scaling HP already baked into its numbers. The full table deliberately lives in exactly one document so it can never again drift into two conflicting versions.
How to Use the "Stat Scores" Column: scores are listed as Primary/Secondary/Tertiary/Dump. Assign the Primary score to the enemy's main stat based on its Archetype (e.g., Might for a Brute), and distribute the other three as you see fit.

B. Encounter Balancing Made Clear
The balancing formula remains simple: the total Threat Level of all enemies should be roughly equal to the number of Player Characters.
