Special Progression Paths
Characters who dedicate themselves to mastering either the arcane or martial disciplines unlock unique benefits as their power grows. These benefits trigger when you spend AP to advance a relevant skill; they do not apply during initial character creation.
Combat Prowess
A warrior's focused dedication to their combat style hones their body and instincts to a razor's edge.
The Adept Benefit: When you first reach the Adept tier in any Combat Skill (One-Handed, Two-Handed, Archery), your body becomes tougher. You gain a permanent +2 bonus to your maximum HP.
The Expert Benefit: When you first reach the Expert tier in any Combat Skill, your stamina becomes legendary. You gain a permanent +2 bonus to your maximum FP.
The Master Benefit: When you first reach the Master tier in any Combat Skill, you have achieved true mastery of the battlefield. You may choose one other Combat or Armor skill where you are an Apprentice. That skill is immediately promoted to Adept for free.
Arcane Studies
A mage's focused study in one school of magic naturally unlocks a basic understanding of others. The free promotions granted by this rule cannot advance a skill beyond the Adept tier.
The Adept Benefit: When you first reach the Adept tier in any magic skill, you may choose one of your Novice magic skills. That skill is immediately promoted to Apprentice for free.
The Expert Benefit: When you first reach the Expert tier in any magic skill, you may choose one of your Apprentice magic skills. That skill is immediately promoted to Adept for free.
The Master Benefit: When you first reach the Master tier in any magic skill, you may choose another one of your Apprentice magic skills. That skill is immediately promoted to Adept for free.

Progression in Practice:
After 1 Adventure (1 AP): A player will typically spend their first point to either promote their main Apprentice skill to Adept or broaden their base by promoting two Novice skills to Apprentice.
After 2 Adventures (2 AP): A player might have an Adept skill and an Apprentice skill. They could save their second point, combining it with their first, to promote their Adept skill straight to Expert.
A Veteran Character (5 AP earned): A long-running character might have spent their points as follows:
1 AP to get their main skill to Adept.
1 AP to get two utility skills to Apprentice.
2 AP to get their main skill to Expert.
1 AP to increase their max HP by 2.

Guiding Player-Created Martial Techniques
As martial characters reach the Adept, Expert, and Master tiers in their combat skills, they unlock the ability to create and evolve their own signature techniques. The complete rules for this player-facing system, called "The Master's Form," are found in the Player's Guide.
Your role as the GM is not to dictate the technique, but to facilitate its creation using the following principles:
Encourage Thematic Concepts: Help the player translate their cool idea ("a whirlwind of strikes," "an unstoppable charge") into a specific Martial Style (Agility, Might, etc.). The name and description are as important as the mechanics.
Verify the Budget: Ensure the player's choices are valid. If they choose two Minor Drawbacks, they can only select two Minor Effects. If they choose one Major Drawback, they can only select one Major Effect.
Trust the System: The Drawback-for-Effect system is designed to be balanced. A powerful technique will always have significant costs or risks. Trust that a player's choices will create a balanced move, and focus on making it feel awesome in the game.
Be a Fan: When a player finally unleashes their Master-tier "World-Breaker" technique, describe the devastating impact. When they use their "Perfect Opening," describe the enemy's shocked expression. These moves are the ultimate reward for a player's dedication to their character's pathΓÇöcelebrate them.


Awarding Loot
Rewards in this system are handled in two ways: Incidental Loot dropped by enemies, and the Major Treasure found at the adventure's conclusion.
Incidental Loot: Most of the gold, basic potions, and mundane equipment the party finds will come directly from the bodies of their defeated foes, as detailed in their monster stat blocks.
Major Treasure: The significant magical items and large sums of gold are the ultimate prize for completing the adventure, typically found in Section 5. Use the following framework to budget the total rewards for an adventure based on the Party's Tier.
